    <h3 style="color: white; margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">What is the "Universal Frequency"?</h3>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        If you look into meditation or sound therapy, you will eventually hear about the <a href="/frequency?hz=432"
            style="color: var(--primary); text-decoration: underline;" target="_blank">432 Hz</a> vs. <a
            href="/frequency?hz=440" style="color: var(--primary); text-decoration: underline;" target="_blank">440
            Hz</a> debate. Today, almost all modern music is tuned to a standard where the musical note "A" equals <a
            href="/frequency?hz=440" style="color: var(--primary); text-decoration: underline;" target="_blank">440
            Hz</a>. However, many musicians and audiophiles advocate for tuning instruments to A = <a
            href="/frequency?hz=432" style="color: var(--primary); text-decoration: underline;" target="_blank">432
            Hz</a>, which is often dubbed the "Universal Frequency" or "Earth's Frequency."
    </p>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Proponents of <a href="/frequency?hz=432" style="color: var(--primary); text-decoration: underline;"
            target="_blank">432 Hz</a> argue that it mathematically aligns better with the patterns found in nature and
        the universe, resulting in a sound that feels warmer, clearer, and more soothing to the human ear. Whether you
        view <a href="/frequency?hz=432" style="color: var(--primary); text-decoration: underline;" target="_blank">432
            Hz</a> as a profound mathematical truth of the universe or simply a slightly warmer, mellower tuning
        standard, it is undeniably popular for relaxing ambient music.
    </p>

